{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_fogler_ver01/data/sn83030214/00206532592/1921012701/0772.xml":{"full_text":"i?m go?k S?ilnme\nFir*t to Last?the Truth: Ne^s?Edi?\ntorials?A'tven [?ementa\nMwbtt o? the A.idit Burviiu of Circulations.\nTHURSDAY, JANUARY 27. 192?\nOwtied b? New Tork TMfcUlM tnc, t New Y'irV\nO.TlffiNtlAi. Published dailj OrrtMi Raid. iYeal\ndont; O. Tamo? Rocen. Vice-PrwUam. Halon\nKof?r? Held, f^-wtart. R E Maxflrid. Tre?*urer\nAddraw, Tnbun? Building. ISA Nassau Street. New\n?orfc. Telephon?, RwKioan 3uC0.\n?CaSCRIPTtON RATES- Bj malV. including\nPogtatA *X THE L'MTKlt STATES.\nOu? SU On?\nRj Mall rvwtpatd. Te?r Month?. Mon'h.\nXnOr and Su-.Jajr.?U.09 $?.00 *1.\"0\nOn? are**. SSc\nTHiXs ?nl?. WOO 5.00 .SS\nOn? ?reek. KOo.\nhunt]?; onlf. #.00 2.?5 .#0\niftmdaj only. Canada...... ?00 8.25 .?5\nFORK1QN RAT?:?\nD*Hy a\">d Sunday.$26 00 I1S.W fS.49\nDa?? on:v. w 40 8*0 L#S\n.-uiida> only.*.. 9.75 5.12 .8?\nEnterad at the. Pwioffl?. New York aa {Second\nCtaai Mai' Matter.\nGUARANTY\nVan ?an purchase merchandise advertised In THE\nTRIBUNE with abialu e wfoty?4or If di ?atl?fne?\ntto? r-sul'.s In any rasa THE TRIBUNE guaran\ntea? to ?a> vonr n on ba.k uoon r?xiue*t. No fad\ntap?. No quibbling. We make cuoil promptly if\ntil? advortlser do? not.\nMBMBER OF THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe A*aov?a!;v| Press la ex.-lualrely entitled to\ntb? use for republloation of all m-w? dispatches\ncredited to t: ?r .sot otherwise credited in this\npaper, and ala the local news of spoutaneoua\norigin published herein.\nAU rights o? republlcaUoo of all othai matter\nMil n asi' are rte>'rvfd\nGetting the Facts First\nTo settle the traction problems\nmore than a home rule debate is\nnecessary.\nThe Governor claims for the\nstate exclusive power to dictate\ntares and the conditions of traction\noperation and that in the applica- j\ntion of this power the state may j\nabrogate contracts. I\nBut there are many who hold that\neven though the state in legal the?\nory has absolute power it is unwise\nand unfair to devolve it in whole or\nIn part on the city. Such are per- j\nsuaded that it would be so mon?\nstrously unjust for the state to ex?\ntinguish self-government that an at?\ntempt to do so would inevitably j\nbreak down.\nBut whichever way the debate i\nended the result would not touch\nthe practicalities of the subway\nproblem. The real business could\nnot be attacked until after the state\nhad established Its autocracy or-the\ncity its independence or partial in?\ndependence. Thus overemphasis of\nthe home rule issue, whether by a\njudicial Governor or by a dema?\ngogic Mayor who would distract at?\ntention from the misdeeds of his\nadministration, may be deprecated.\nThe first need is for a sound basis\nof fact. What are the prospects of\nfuture subway income? Has the i\ncorner been turned? With lowered\nprices for coal and other ?upplies\nand more efficient labor, oven\nthough the? present wage scale Is\nto endure until 1922, ioes the 5\ncent fare plus the 2 cents per pas?\nsenger that the city now contribute\nout of taxes suffice to meet operat-1\ning expense? and interest on the\nsums actually invested? Until the\npublic is adequately informed it\n\\Jacks basis for solid judgment as to\nwhat fare revisions, if any, are\nnecessary.\nAs things now are there is a con-\ntract under which the passenger\npays a nickel and the city agrees to\ncontribute up to 2 cents more per\npassenger. This extra 2 cents is\nnow being paid, but the subway in?\ncome Is not quite enough to meet\noperating expenses and the charges\nOh private funds put into the sub?\nways. It follows that while further\ndiminution of net income would\nbe at the expense of private in?\nvestors an increase would not give\nsubway bondholders their full in?\nterest and begin to give the city\ntreasury something to offset the 2\ncent subvention. But the few surely i\nknow what may be expected.\nFinally there is the big question\nof what concessions the real owners\nof the subway are willing to make\nto rid themselves of the obliea-;\ntions of a contract which they re?\ngard as onerous and which estab?\nlishes a species of lien against their\ninvestments. No one speaking with\nany authority has matured an un?\nderstandable proposal. Thus there\nis nothing actual to consider, and\nthe injection of the horre rule ques?\ntion in no wise supplies '.he lack.\nBefore proceeding to action\nwhich is now non-pertinent and\nbased on shadowy guesswork the\nLegislature should ascertain the\nF f&cts. Hence, tjie first luty of any\nnew state-control agency should be\nto inquire. What would then be j\ndone would depend on the results\no* the inquiry. This woild seem to i\nbe better policy than to adopt a\nrigid policy first and then to find\n?JTit how it ia to be aponed.\nSacrificing the Filipinos\nWaiting for the approval of Sec?\nretary Colby on his return, it is said,\ni? the draft of an agreement on\nthe Japanese-California land contro?\nversy, reached by Ambassadors Mor?\nris ami Shidchara.\nIn the main the agreement teems\nsatisfactory, but there is one item\nraoat extraordinary, Altho'ugfc Jup\nancftft Immigration into this country\nand Hawaii is to be forbidden, it is\npovided that the exclusion -hall not\napply to the Phtippines. Into those\nta?ardt the Japanese are- to be al?\nlowed to enter freely, They can go\nthere by the hundred? of thousand?,\nif they wish, without regard to the\nwishes or the interests of the Fili?\npino?.\n7he probable r?unit? are not. difFl\net??t to force?. Th* Jipa new.? will\naiov? Into the Island? in great nurn\nbar?, afthay ha%? Utto Hawaii. Be-\ning further on than the Filipinos in\nmany ways, they will acquire the\ngood land and exploit the nativos.\nThe natives will, sooner or lutcr, ob?\nject, and collisions will arise. The\nJapanese government will naturally\nbe inclined to uphold the contentions\nof those with whom they feel nation?\nal and racial symp-ithy. Moreover,\nin the event of trouble in the Pacific,\nthe Japanese*will nave established In\nthe' Philippines a force able, to seize\nthem.\nThe project thus seems a studied\none to abandon the Filipinos?to sac?\nrifice them in order to secure\nJapan's acceptance of a bargain\npleasing to California. It is not\nj necessary to point out that to make\nmerchandise of the wards of the na\ntion in this fashion is indefensible.\ni The Philippines are a thousand\nI times more threatened with an alien\nj inundation than is California, and\nnational honor requires that we do\nnot sell out a dependent people be\nj hind their backs.\n?_.\nSympathy for Mr. Schwab\nThe warm sympathy and respect\nfor Mr. Schwab expressed '\"by his in?\nvestigators represent the general\nfeeling. It was the hope and ex?\npectation of every one that the\ncharge made against him would\nprove unfounded. To have believed\nanything else would have been to\ndoubt the elemental patriotism of a\ngreat and typical American. The\naccusation was incredibie, and there\n?3 general rejoicing that its falsity\nhas been promptly established?and j\nprofound sympathy for the victim j\nof misdirected zeal.\nThe episode looks both way3 on\nthe question of publicity. It gives\nthe clear reason why business men\ndread investigations in the open\nHowever scrupulously honest and\nlaw-abiding a man may be,, there is\nalways some item which, partly re?\nvealed, unfairly stated, will justify\nsensational headlines. And it is a\nrare investigator who is above such\nmethods.\nBut the case also suggests the\nmore important truth that a denial\nof publicity works even worse evils\n?if found out. There may have\nbeen excellent reasons for calling off\nthe investigators of the Shipping\nBoard books. But they should not\nhave been heeded under the circum-\nstances. Better the most unfair and\nhostile investigation than the sus?\npicions engendered by a burked\nrevelation. The Schwab charge i\nwould undoubtedly have been dis?\ncarded without a hearing if full j\naccess to the books had been granted.\nFor better, for worse, complete\npublicity is the only way for quasi- I\npublic business in a republic. The\nunfortunate and regrettable insult\nto Mr. Schwab only re?nforces the j\nrule.\nNew York-?Some Day\nThe New York and New Jersey\nPort and Harbor Commission never\nknows when it has been rebuffed, j\nIt is composed of men who look to\nthe future, who do not think that,\nbecause New York's primacy as an\nAmerican port came to it through j\nthe bounty of nature, we can retain\nthat primacy forever by merely eit-!\nting back and contemplating the j\nmagnificent range and unequaled j\nlavishness of our water front. It is\nalso aware that, contrary to common\nconviction, the city's insularity is\nj not an advantage, but rather a se\n1 rious disadvantage, under modern\nconditions of transportation and corn-\nmerce. New York is a city with\nlamentably inadequate terminal i\nfacilities. And first class terminal\nfacilities are a necessity for a com-\nmercial community which means to\nglow.\nNew York cannot now feed or sup-\nply itself economically because of her\nriver barriers. Cost of distribution j\nhere is excessive, and every resident,\nand business man feels the burden.\nFailure to see that a port or com-1\nmercial center must modernize itself,\nhowever overwhelming its natural\nadvantages once were, has been driv-\ning bus ness away from this city\nand mating living conditions here'\nharder. Foreign trade is not actual-\nly declining, because so many steam-(\nj ship lines have long made this port j\ntheir main base of operation. But\nother pcrts can give cheaper and j\nbetter terminal service and are eco-\n1 nomically in a position to cut into i\nour trade.\nA scientific scheme for the unifica?\ntion of the port, under a treaty with\nNew Jersey, has been hanging fire\nfor many months. The Hylan ad-1\nministration has opposed it, quite\ncharacteristically. But the Port and\nHarbor Development Commission is\nSnot discouraged. It has just put\nforward a supplementary scheme for j\na consolidation of freight facilities.;\nwhich will ?ink up Manhattan ana!\nI the Jersey side of the Hudson and\neliminate the costly river short haul.\nThe plan is bold and comprehensive,\nIt would connect a Joint freight tcr\nminal in West Hoboken by tunnel\nwith various distributing points in\nManhattan, insure the easy entry\nAnd ejrresft of freight and mv* timo\nt and money in distribution. By\neventually minimizing harbor llght\n?rag? it would free the piers for\nocean business and get rid of the'\nrailroad tracks along our North\n'Liver front.\nMaybe this pro'ect will alr-o en- j\n?counter local Indifference. But It. ia\nsound ?nd must antue day bo real-\niaed it New Y oik la to supply her\npeople economically and retaWher\nplace of eminence as port and a\nmart.\nWhen To Be BuFtish\nIn a world all ?nude to order there\nwould be neither \"peaks\" nor \"hol?\nlows\" in husinesa?things would\nmove along evenly, expanding slowly\nto meet the needs of increasing pop?\nulation and higher standards.of liv?\ning. But the world isn't made to or?\nder, so we have periods of frenzied\nactivity, followed by depression,\ndullness and great activity again.\nUnfortunately, no one has succeed?\ned in devising a formula by which\nthe various phases of the cycle can\nbe measured with exactitude. So we\ncannot give statistical data to show\nprecisely when the turns for the bet\nter or worse will come. Nevertheless,\nthere is one infallible way to fore\nc.^st the coming of depression us well\nas the return of prosperity. When\nthe great majority of us are wildly\noptimistic an early crash in business\nis inevitable. And when the major?\nity are pessimistic and ready to con?\nsign the country to the dogs it is as\ncertain as anything can be that pros?\nperity is just around the economic\ncorner.\nIt is so at present. Just as most\nof us were overopti'mistic when the\nrecent boom was about to reach its\ncrest, so pessimism has been over?\ndone of late. Business in this coun?\ntry is not going to the dogs?now or\never. It is going to do just as it has\nin the past: that is, continue, with\nminor interruptions, to expand in a\nmanner that will so enhance the na?\ntion's prosperity as to enable all of\nus to enjoy a higher standard of liv?\ning. The upturn may not be visible\nto every one for a while, but it is\nunder way right now. There is rqore\nthan enough work to be done, and\npresently we shall be doing it.\n\"Wealth,\" says the economist, \"is\nthat for use and enjoyment of which\npeople will give money.\" Gauged by J\nthat standard, we are wealthier than\nwe ever were before. Presently peo-\npie will begin to understand that\nfact. When they do depression will\nbe a thing of the past.\nThe time to be bullish is now.\nThe Navy Bu?ding Program\nThe policy of building battleships\nand cruisers for the navy is now j\nunder consid?ration by Congress. A\nwise decision is of vital interest to\nthe country.\nThere are eleven super-dread?\nnoughts under construction. Two\nof these, the California and the\nMaryland, are so near completion\nthat they should be added to the\nfleet. The Colorado, the Washing--\nton and the West Virginia are well\nadvanced. These three, with the I\nMaryland, would form a strong di-1\nvision of 16-inch-gun ships. Their\ncompletion may be justified.\nThe remaining six dreadnoughts j\nare less than 26 per cent complete.\nIn view of the menace to battleships\nof present type .from submarine and\nair attack, the completion of these\nsix ships may be very unwise. It I\nwould seem sound policy to stop\nwork on them for the present. It\nmay be necessary in view of the\nIndiana experiment to provide them\nwith an armored deck to protect\nthem from bombing attack. Or if\ntheir construction is delayed for a\ntime, it may be advisable to com- j\nplete them as carriers of heavy I\nbombing and torpedo planes. We are\nsadly In need of such types. An of?\nficer of distinction declares:\nThere can be no doubt that The j\nTribune's Idea of a three-plunc fleet\nis correct, and that what we need I\nnow is to put emphasis upon the i\nupper and lower planes. We have;\nenough of the surface plane at th?\npresent time. I would oven like to,\nsee the building of sonio of our bat-!\ntleships abandoned to ?lake money\navailable for these auxiliary pur-\nposes.\nIn addition to eleven dread-\nnougl there are six big battle\ncrui building. When originally\ndesi\" the need of these ships was\ngen. ty recognized. but to-day\ntheir utility is decidedly questioned\nat home and abroad. Inasmuch as\ntheir construction is only just begun\n?they are not more than 10 peri\ncent complete?it is believed that\nwork upon these ships, as at pr?s- j\nont designed, should stop until the i\nparamount needs of the fleet and the\ngoverning influence of new weapons\nare carefully considered.\nIt is important to noto that the\nhull and machinery of incompleted\nbattleships and battle-cruisers may\nbe fully utilized and all waste pro\nvented if these ships are ultimately\ntransformed into modern airplane\nand torpedo plane carriers to bring\nour fleet to a proper standard of\nafflciency in aviation. One of the\nablest officers in our navy says: \"It\nmay be that within a reasonable\ntime it will be realized that an air?\nplane carrier, able to steam at 35\nknots and to carry ten torpedo\nplanes and twenty fighting planes, is\na capital ship and is more powerful\nas ?n offensive weapon than any\nOther type of capital ship can be.\"\n8o much for the big ship pro- i\ngram. There are ten scout-cruisers j\nbuilding, many of them well nd-\nvenced, They should bo completed,\nregardless of the battleship policy.\nWo need some fast surfac? ships in\nthe fleet.\nIt Is manifest that th* forty-seven j\nsubmarines .vre sadly needed. Thefo j\nare no modern submarines in eiir\nfleet to-day. We will be moro or less\nI helpless without them.\nThere is but one safe and saae pol?\nicy. We must not be satisfied with\na navy that would have been strong\nj in 1916. We want a navy that will\nbe st?rong in 192*: and in the years\nto come. Congress .should imme?\ndiately appoint a committee to inves?\ntigate this subject thoroughly, and\nthe committee should call officers to\ntestify frankly and fearlessly. By\ndoing this we muy save hundreds of\nmillions in providing a modern\nthree-plane navy.\nA Strong Bishop\nThe choice of Dr. Manning to be\nthe next Protestant Episcopal Bishop\nof New .York brings to that post\nability of the first rank. Both as the\nexecutive head of a great parish and\nas preacher and pastor he ranks\namong the ablest spiritual leaders of\nthe city. His su< i ess now is the vic?\ntory of a strong man who prevails on\nhis merits?there is no hint of that\ncomprunii.se upon a second best or\ninoffensive personality which\noften occurs in conventions, diocesan\nand otherwise.\nNo one, we think, will take loo\nseriously the somewhat, heated state?\nments made in Dr. Manning's name\nbut without his authority touching\nthe application of curb bits to rest?\nless clergymen. Dr. Manning has\nthe strength to use a bit; he has also\nshown in his own parish a breadth of\noutlook which bears testimony of a\ngenerosity and largeness of mind\nand negatives any narrow use of\nstrength. The task which faces him\nis one of union upon essentials, and\nhe will belie his whole career if he\nadministers his high office upon any\nother plan.\nThere will be especial rejoicing\nthat the stanch Americanism and\nactive patriotism of Dr. Manning\nhave been thus recognized. His voice j\nwas a powerful one for right during\nthe war. The enemies he then made\nare greatly t-to his credit. He will\ntake office with the hearty good will\nof the entire unhyphenated popula?\ntion of the city.\nAfter Pvohibition\nFear Expressed That Relief Will\nBe Found in Worse Vices\nTo the Editor of The Tribune.\nSir: I was much interested In read?\ning the letter of \"Long Island\" in your\niasue of January 20, in which the writer I\nstates the effects of prohibition on men\nwho wen? formerly moderate drinkers,\nand who now drink to excess.\nThese men would be interested, I j\nthink, in reading The Psychology of\nRelaxation, by G. P. W. Patrick, in\nwhich one chapter Is devoted to the\n\"Psychology of Alcohol.\" The writer\nstates that the craving for ethyl alcohol\nis age old and was known to \"the lake\ndwellers of the Neolithic Age.\" Also\nthat it waa autochihonic, \"arising in?\ndependently in all parts of the world.\"\nThe Eskimos, apparently, were im?\nmune, possibly because they had no\nfruit or grain from which to distill al?\ncohol. However, one recalls with amuse?\nment how ?the Eskimos gorged them?\nselves with Dr. Grenfcll's gift of gum-\ndrops; alao our own lato craving for\ncandy and the enormous quantities now\nconsumed. Some tell us that our systems\nturn candy into alcohol 1 (Shall candy\nalso bo prohibited?)\nStatistics clearly prove that the con?\nsumption of alcohol has increased. I\nWhereas in ISfiO the per capita con-\nsumption In thli country was 4.08 gal?\nlons, In 1914 it was 22.49 gallons. The\nrecords also show?and this a body blow\nto the cause of prohibition?that as tho\nconsumption of alcohol increased j\ndrunkenness decreased. The problem\nwas gradually solving itself. Who would j\nthink nowadays of giving one's servant\nsufficient liquor for several days' de-\nbauch? No one, I venture to assert. Yet j\nthis is exactly what George Washing\nton did. It must be admitted that con-\nsidcrable progress has been made along\nthese lines.\nin the year 1914 1,593 illicit stills\nwere seized by the Commissioner o? In\nterna] Revenue. It would be interesting\nto know how many were confiscated in\n1920, that is, since prohibition.\nJust what does this craving mean?\nTo q'iote from Dr. Patrick's book, \"It is\nthe expression of the desire fo, release\nfrom the tension of the strenuous life.\"\nAnd again, \"W? ihus trace the desire\nfor alcohol to the inherent need of mind\nand body for relaxation, a need normally\nsupplied by all the varied forma of\nplay and sport.\"\nMy own fear is that something worse\nthan alcohol will take its place, which\nwill in turn be prohibited. OHIO.\nCleveland, Ohio,' Jan. 34, 1921.\nQuakers in Ireland\nTo the Editor of The Tribune\nSir: A statement by Frederic C.\nHowe, a speaker last Sunday night at\ntin Community Church Forum, that\nQuakers fled from England to the south\nand west of Ireland, was challenged,\nand rightly so, by a man in the au?\ndience.\nFor the edification of Mr. Howe I\nwill state that the founder of Penn?\nsylvania, William Penn, a Quaker, was\nclapped into prison with Thomas Ece\nand some others by the Mayor of i\nCork in 1868, for attending a Quaker\nmeeting, This is certainly at vari\nanco with the staterhi ni o? Mr. Howe\nthat Ireland waa a place of refuge for\noppressed English Quakers.\nPenn was sent there by his fut!.er\nSir William Penn, sn eminent Engll h\nadmiral, to loofc after his estates In\ntho County of Cork.\nSANDY FOUNDATION.\nNew York. Jan. 2*4, 1921.\nA I -Ugh Standard\ntFrmn The Philadelphia North American)\nE lied king M is said, woul like to\nlive In America, but poverty prevents;!\nIt is understood they express doubts\nabout being able to kcop up with tho j\nstandards o? living of tho American I\nworkiogmnn?\nThe Conning Tower\nYankee Bards and British Reviewers\nThe scarlet of American excess creeps\nr<i< n into the pale blue of American son\nj timentality. The sentimental atti\ntuda toward women sometimes\ntakes a strange lyrical form, particular\nI ly in the newspapers.?W. L. George in\nThe Februaty Harper's.]\nj Lady, pray pardon mine excess,\nBut when your simple suppiiant woos,\nDespite his Yankee scarletness,\nHe has Those Sentimental Blues.\nYet. though the yappiest of hicks,\nUnsentimental as a derrick,\nlearned a lot of mushy tricks\nFrom Robert Herrick.\ni 'Love in my bosom like a bee''\ni From Lodge 1 lift that lovely line).\n\"Love still hath something of the sea\"\n(Sedley). \"And I'll not ask for wine\"\n(Jonson). From Byron's Athens Maid,\nFrom girls in Wither, Cowlej Fletcher,\nTei i Waller, Dobson, Praed\nI've swiped, you betcher.\no?i. British bards, studied so oit,\nI slushy he my roundelay,\nIf tender be my heart and soft?\nYe made, me what I am to-day.\nRut still, the heart of this here bard,\nFor all its frequent jeopardizing,\nlias made itself robust and hard\nFrom exercising.\nWell, there were fewer criminal con?\nvictions in 1920 than in 1919 in tho\nState of New York. This proves either\nthat prohibition is successful or that it\nmakes little difference how poor or how\nhard to get booze is.\nTry as we will, we can't got further\nthan the first, line of a parody beginning\n\"Emperor Jones, shot another bullet.\"\nThe Diary of Our Own Samuel Pepye\nJanuary 25? Up, and so cold in the\nhouse I could not hold a razor in my\nhand, so went unshaven. To the office,\nwhere till near five, and so to Neysa's,\nto wish her a birthday wish, and find\nMiss Julia Furnham there, full of beauty\nand sanity. R. Ivea come, too, and E.\nTracy, and Mistress Julia Hoyt, und we\nhad some cakes, but not so much as a\nglass of water to drink, yet gay as\nmight be. So home, upon an omnibuss,\nto dinner, and read O. Graeve's \"Tho\nBrown Moth,\" an interesting story, und\none character in it, of Howard Barton,\ndrawn with great skill. To a barber's\nto have my hair cut and ho put some\n\"tonic\" on my hair, aibeit I did not ask\nhim to, which put me out o? sorts. To\nbed, and read A. Bennett's play \"Body\nand Soul,\" of no great Interest, and so\nto sleep.\n2(5? Early up, and to the office, and\nR. Hayes come in, and G. Parsons, and j\nA. Dawson, and H. Canby, all talking\nover my desk; yet they all have chided\nme at times for that I did not do better j\nv/riting, when, Lord, I do as well aa ever j\nI can. At my stint till finished with it, j\nand bo to see Mistress Hilda, and then\nwith J. Kern *o dinner and to see\n\"Peburau,\" which I hope will be better\nto see than it wa3 to read.\nJapan and the United States, It ap?\npears, ara quarreling over the Yappian\nWay.\nIdeal Tour No. 361\nWe were crowded In the flivver,\nKot a soul would dare to crank\nit was midnight out by Newark,\nAmi no gas waa in the tank.\n'TiBfa fearful thing In printer\nTo be made to push a Ford,\nLoaded up with Suo, and Johnnie.\nAlice, Bert and May aboard.\nSo we panted there In ?Hence),\nOn tho air our frosty breaths;\nWhile we wondered if the papers\nWould contain a l?3t of deaths.\nAnd as thus we shoved in silence,\nEach one wishing for a nip,\n\"Have some' hooch I\" a pusher shouted,\nAs ho reachwl unto his hip.\nBut our ?lttlo daughter whispered\nAi wo tried to pull the cork\n\"Ain't there Standard Oil in/ Jemey,\nJust the same as in New Y'-ork 1\"\nThen we kissed that little maiden,\nAnd we drank to better beer\nAnd we ran our bus to Newark,\nFull of ?raaoiine and cheer.\nBinds*?.\nHow unlyrlcal the advertiser! Says\nhe: \"Read the book Miss Lulu Bett. See\nthe pluy Miss Lulu Bett. You can get\nthe novel at any bookstore, $1.75 net.\"\nWore it not better, us Milton said,'thus?\nRead the book Miss Lulu Bett;\nSee the play Miss Lulu Bett;\nAt any bookstore you can get\nTho book. It's one seventy-five (that's\nnet).\nThrenody\nOn an evening of black snow\n1 walked along the causeway,\nWishing that I too might melt\nBetween the agitated lingers\nOf a stuttering, intolerable sea.\n-Amy Lowell, in The Unpartizan Review.\nWishing is well enough, Miss Lowell.\nBut for melthj-*?\nThere's nothing like banting.\n\"Never,\" writes Gertrude Hall in\nSeribner's, \"do I come upon a chapter\non dreams but read It. Never does\nany one talk about dreams but I listen.\nI induce people to tell me what they\nhave dreamed.\" Well, we aro just tho\nother way. We skip all chapters on\ndreams; the recital of a dream causes\nour attention to wander; and our\norisons, if any, are made to people beg?\nging that they won't tell what they have\ndreamed.\nOf course, there are Interesting\ndreams. There wna Shelley's celebrated\nrecital:\nI arise from dreams of thee,\nAnd n spirit in my feet\nHas led ma?who knows how??\nTo my chamber window, sweetl\nAr-k I''rend?he knows. And\n'.here nro our own dreams.\nOur most frequently recurring dronm\nis that there is one n\"eond left to press\ntime and it is impossible to think of tho\none additional line wo neod to ?ill.\nWhat do you make of ihut. Dr. Freud7\nF. P. A.\nTHE ONLY EMBARGO THERE IS ON TRADE WITH RUSSIA\nCopyright. 1921, New Tork Tribune Ino.\nii.. _, _:_ i\n!YotX?. EjvvB^RAOl\nVi? J?e\\J|(M?\"MCa I\nR?t\nKBBmaCt\niLOOi-v HERE- I DONT-v\ni WAN! THESF. Box S j\n\"S\nAGAINST rtiVVi\nAV^4>.\nAt-L f?tClHT, \"7\nN0-?<V4 WHAT EuS?3\nv-jE Dom't ^-.iEvE?in iv?one r\nA.? M?DiijM OT fcACHAjMOCT\nr*\\)?\\? hOvv DO?\nvou want r o j\nPa-< for. this M\nGeneral Wood's Career\nA Summary of Extraordinary Quali?\nfications for Cabinet Service\nTo V;\\o Editor of The Tribune.\nSir: I suggest?and there is no \"may\n1 not\" about It?that every one who\nsupported Leonard Wood last summer\nrnsi?tently write President-elect Har?\nding in support of your efforts to se?\ncure him a place in the new Cabinet.\nSince the death of ex-President\nRoosevelt there is probably no man\nliving whose activities have extended\nover so many countries, been so varied\nand so efficient in each case as have\nthese of Leonard Wood.\nLeonard Wood has performed not?\nable services for America in Great\nBritain, France, Germany, Switzerland,\nSpain, Malta, India, Ceylon, Singapore\nand other Straits Settlements; in the\nBritish Protectorate of Egypt, in Java,\nDutch and British Borneo, the Philip?\npin?) Islands, the Argentine Republic\nthe Panama Canal Zone, in Cuba, in\nPorto Rico and in forty-six of oui\nfcrty-eight states.\nHis services embrace twenty-sever\nnational activitie's of an executive ant\nadministrative nature, thirteen of\nbusiness nature, five of a diplomat?\ncharacter, six of social and institu\ntior.al reform and betterment, sevei\nhumanitarian activities of recognize*\ninternational importance and eievei\nintern tionaj investigations of fj/reigi\ncolonial systems. In addition, he ha\nheld seven administrative militar\ncommands.\nThere are few people who kno\\\nthat Leonard Wood has been a slur\ndoctor, a commissioner of customs,\njustice in international disputes, a di\nrector of a university, an agricultura\ncredit banker, etc.\nConsidering his character and hi\nadministrative and humanitarian worl\nit is silly to consider him a mere mi!\nitary man or to attempt to exclud\nhim from the Cabinet because he ha\nbeen honored by the uniform of th\nUnited States Army nnd has honore\nit for many years.\nIt is impossible, even briefly, to giv\nany adequate indication of the man\nkinds of service he has rendered.\nAs a Secretary of the Interior an\nDirector of National Relief, Lconai\nWood's reform and relief work in Cul\nhas never been equaled. Cuba is foi\ntimes as large as Belgium; Wood ni\nonly spent millions to feed its star\ning people and rehabilitate its indu\ntries, but he made the people so pro\nporous within twelve months that th<\nthemselves were able to pay for the\nrelief und reconstruction work. Oth\nmen have spent millions in rfjievh\nstarving people in all parts of tl\nworld; but no man except Wood h\nc\\nr taken charge of a starving pe\npie whose land;, had been d?vast?t\nb> years of war, put them to wo\nand made it possible for them to p,\nfor their own relief.\nAs a Secretary of Labor he indue\nwithout any friction whatever, an t\ntire semi-indolent Latin nation of\nsemi-tropical climate to go to w<\nand to reniain at work.\nAs a constructive legislator he sup\nvioed the drafting of a national den\ncratic constitution; the recodlficat\nof a natlon't laws, the drafting of 8\ncial educational and public char\nlaws and of special railway laws so\nin advance of their time that they h\n.unce born copied by twenty-two ot\ngovernments. In addition, ho re\nganlr.ed the entire Cuban system\njudicial procedure.\nAs n reformer of 'nsanc asylums,\nabolished in Cuba the horrible syai\nof keeping the Insane In little bo\non wheels, built model ?unitary\nlums, gave tho inmates medicil care\nand provided work i?nd amusement for\nthem.\nA3 a founder of orphans' homes,\nWood established live large mo'iei chil?\ndren's homes and later persons?.y su?\npervised the adoption uf children by\nprivate families, thus saving ?ens of\nthousands of waifs, parents not known,\nwho were begging in the streets of\nCuba.\nConsider him next as a commissioner\nof education. The mass of Cuban chil?\ndren had never attended school; of\nthe people, 57 per cent could not even\nr*ad; then- was not a single govern?\nment schoolhouse anywhere in Cuba.\nWood built two fchoolhouses in every\ntown of five hundred people. In two\nyears he had established 3,800 schooL,\n*A-ith 200,000 children in attendance.\nNo educator of the world bas so re?\nmarkable a record.\nAs an ambassador General Wood has\nrendered little known though valuable\nservice. He has been Special Ambas?\nsador to Argentina, Special Envoy to\nGermany and Frence, Special Envoy\nto Spain, Special Investigator of Co?\nlonial Systems in Malta, Egypt, India,\nCeylon, Singapore and Borneo and\nSpecial Envoy to Switzerland1 and tc\nEngland.\nAs a diplomat Leonard Wood tact\nfully harmonized many difficult inter?\nnational affairs. Ho induced the Cu?\nbans, who had been oppressed and\ncruelly treated by the Spaniards foi\nfour hundred years, sincerely to pro?\npose a toast for the health of King\nAlfonso and led the Spaniards, win\nhad for centuries despised the Cu?\nbans, cordially to respond by drinking\nto the health of the nc* Cuban Re?\npublic. Yet the greatest Allied states?\nmen of to-day have not been able tc\ninduce the Germans to drinH in i\nfriendly manner to the health ol\nFrance, nor hav? they beei. able to lea*\nthe French to toast the health of tn<\nnew German rej-ublic.\nit is possible to continue; space onlj\nprevents. Again I urge every Ameri\ncan who realizes the difficult interna?\ntional affairs and the serious domesti<\nproblems that must be adjusted in th<\nnext few years to write Insistently\nPresident-elect Harding, requesting\nthe inclusion of Leonard Wood as t\nmember of the new Cabinet.\nBROWN LANDONE.\nNew York, Jan. 22, 1921.\nWru>t a Farmer Gets for Milk\nTo tho Editor of the Tribune.\nSir: I notice on the front pago of Th?\nTribune to-day an article which states\nthat whereas the xirice of milk paid t<\nthe farmer for February has been re?\nduced one and one-q iarter cents, th?\nmilk distributors will reduce the price\nto the consumer by one cent. Th?\narticle reads as if this were an act o.'\nextreme generosity.\n1 produce grade A milk. In Novem\nber 1 received 8Vj cents and the dis\ntributor 18?4 cents. In February\nwill receive 6% cent?, and the dis\ntributor will have for his share 18*Ji\ncents.\nPut In another way, the price to thi\nfarmer has bien reduced. b:<sod on m;\nactual figures, f'lM: per cent- the prie\nto the consumer 9 per cent?while thi\npublic-spirited distributor will receiv\nonly 2 per cent additional.\nI make no comment; m fact, word;\naro inadequate, and who can blame th\ndistributors as long ?s they can go\naway with it? Ah it Beema easy t\ngot awny with murder these Idaya i?\nNow York, 1 presume ?t is a cause fo\nprofound wonderment that the price 1\nnot advanced to tho consumer.\nFARMER.\nMiddletotwu, j Y., Jan. 18, 1921.\nI On Behalf of Main Street\nA Protest Against Current Pessimism\nTouching \"Gopher Prairie\"\nTo the Editor of The Tribune.\nSir: Perhaps the present writer it\nassuming a good deal in attempting to\nspeak for mainstreetdom. But there is\nnet in all the \"Gopher Prairies\" of\nChristendom a population without some\nredeeming characters who offset the\npetty, vicious, selfish, provincial, ill\ndisposed bunch of inconsequential nicks\nMr. Lewis has given us. In hundreds\nof small towns there are thousands of\nmen and women who are living the\nmost unselfish, patriotic and devoted\nlives. Where, may I ask, did President\nI Li.icoln come, from? And Harding\"\nWhat little out-of-the-way burg pro?\nduced F. P. A.? Think of Irvin Cobb\nbeing raised in a place by the name of\nPaducah! Where do the finincia!\ngeniuses of Wall Street hie themselves\nto at the \"end of a perfect day,\" to uV\naccompanying honk! honk! of the\nroycerolla? Must we make love to\nother men's wives and dance, th*\nshimmy in order to be great? f? that\npatch of Broadway between ?iirty\nfourth Street and Columhus Circle tin\nonly spot in the world which car, pro?\nduce the superhumans who shall save\nthe nation in its hour of peril?yellow\nperil, according to Mi?s Atherton?\nPerish the thought, much as the hick?\nof the world love to roam that Great\nWhite Desertl\nMain Stre' t is an entertaining book\nBut it is onl half of the picture. The\nhalf it describes is exposed with brnM?\nI frankness, but there is much that U\ni sweet and lovely and worth while tsfct\nj has heen left out of the picto?,\nI fpabruun to the contrary notwithstand?\ning. I'm not asking art to make any\ni concessions to Main Street. But I di'\nsolemi.ly protest against the genera!\nchorus from the urbanit?s to the .'Meet\n1 that everybody living west of the Hud?\nson River goes to bed with red mitten?\non during the months of January and\nFebruary and reads nothing but Pil?\ngrim's Progress and the fourt chap\n*nr of the GoBpel accordii.g to St\nMark. Piffle for that stuff. M.C.A.\nMiddletown, N. Y., Jan 11, 1&2L\nSaving Stamps\nTr the Editor of The Tribune.\nSir: Out of $100 worth of stamp?\nused on my mail matter I used 595\nstamps of denominations from 4 cent?\nto SO cents, amounting to $41 39. H?d\nI used 1-fent and 2-ccnt stamps on\nthis mail I would have used 1,96*\n2-cont stamps and 203 1-cent stamps\n?which would be 1,576 more ctamp?\nthan I a